{\fs26\cf1\b FMTApplication}\par
Declaration: 
\line{\f1
class FMTApplication : public FApplication \{\line
}
\par

WYDIWYG: BIFINCL_WINDOW and BIFINCL_THREAD and BIFINCL_APPLICATION\par

FMTApplication must be used instead of {\uldb FApplication}{\v FApplication} in 
programs that use BIF/Thread.\par

Under Windows 3.1 this class ensures that modal message loops (used in 
{\uldb FModalDialog::DoModal()}{\v FModalDialog_DoModal} and 
{\uldb MessageBox()}{\v MessageBox} does not block other threads.\par

\page

#{\footnote FWMainWindowThread}
${\footnote FWMainWindowThread}
+{\footnote defbrowse}
K{\footnote FWMainWindowThread}
{\fs26\cf1\b FWMainWindowThread}\par
Declaration: 
\line{\f1
class FWMainWindowThread : public FMainWindowThread \{\line
}
\par

WYDIWYG: BIFINCL_WINDOW and BIFINCL_THREAD and BIFINCL_APPLICATION\par

FWMainWindowThread is used as the main thread of a program that uses BIF/Window. 
The class starts up BIF/Window in its implementation of FMainThread::Main, so 
the program logically starts executing at {\uldb FApplication::Main()}{\v FApplication_Main}\par

You will normally not need to create subclasses of FWMainWindowThread.\par

